{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534611","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534611"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:48:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:48:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15152"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15152"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.62,0.05,0.12,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7840"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108661"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7840","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7840"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15152"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91030"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3676"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11701"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19110"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40575"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44995"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108661"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of fever, headache, and progressive weakness in her right arm. Her partner reports that the symptoms began with paraesthesia at the site of a 2 cm scratch on her right forearm. They recall that this was sustained when she had startled an animal while working on her fruit farm at night two weeks prior to the onset of symptoms. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell and confused. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. The scratch appears healed but there is decreased sensation and weakness in the right arm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following advice is helpful to prevent contracting the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Avoid contact with bat droppings","Direct exposure to the saliva of flying foxes should be reported immediately","Seek medical attention only if bitten by a visibly unwell wild dog","Wear gloves when handling koalas","Apply mosquito deterrent daily during wet season"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms consistent with Australian bat lyssavirus (ABLV) infection, which is closely related to rabies virus in the lyssavirus infection. The clinical presentation of fever, paraesthesia at the site of injury progressing to weakness, along with confusion are classic features of lyssavirus encephalitis. The incubation period typically ranges from a few weeks to several months, with the two-week period in this case being at the shorter end of the spectrum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect exposure to the saliva of flying foxes should be reported immediately\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct preventive advice. ABLV is transmitted through the saliva of infected bats via bites, scratches, or mucous membrane exposure. It is not transmitted from human-to-human.  Immediate reporting and medical attention after any potential exposure is critical as post-exposure prophylaxis (rabies immunoglobulin and vaccine) is highly effective if administered promptly before symptom onset. Once clinical symptoms develop, as in this case, the disease is almost invariably fatal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAvoid contact with bat droppings\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect advice for preventing ABLV. The virus is not transmitted through contact with bat faeces or urine. It requires direct contact with infectious saliva, typically through bites or scratches.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeek medical attention only if bitten by a visibly unwell wild dog\u003C/strong\u003E is dangerous advice. While dogs can transmit rabies in many countries, they are not known carriers of ABLV in Australia.  All Australian bats should be considered potentially infectious with ABLV regardless of whether they appear healthy or sick thus also identifying if the animal is unwell is not congruent with the animal having the disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWear gloves when handling koalas\u003C/strong\u003E is not relevant to ABLV prevention. While this might be good general advice for handling wild animals, koalas are not known carriers of ABLV in Australia. The virus is specifically associated with bats.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApply mosquito deterrent daily during wet season\u003C/strong\u003E is also not relevant to ABLV prevention. Mosquitoes do not transmit ABLV. This advice would be more relevant for preventing mosquito-borne diseases such as Ross River virus or dengue fever.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Australian bat lyssavirus is transmitted through bites or scratches from infected bats, not through casual contact or droppings.","Post-exposure prophylaxis with rabies immunoglobulin and vaccine should be administered promptly after potential exposure to Australian bat lyssavirus.","All Australian bats should be considered potentially infectious with lyssavirus regardless of their appearance of health."],"references":["Merritt T, Taylor K, Cox-Witton K, et al. Australian bat lyssavirus. Aust J Gen Pract. 2018;47(3):93-96. doi:10.31128/AFP-08-17-4314","Queensland Government. Australian bat lyssavirus | Viral infections [Internet]. Queensland Government Health and Wellbeing. 2023. Available from: https://www.qld.gov.au/health/condition/infections-and-parasites/viral-infections/australian-bat-lyssavirus"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91030"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15152"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91030","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91030"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-12T18:11:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-12T18:17:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7840"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108661"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"38","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/38"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"posi